## What counts as a security issue

When you can, name the untrusted input — parser bytes, an attacker-driven
call sequence, or protocol state — that reaches the issue, and what the
attacker gains. The categories below are not security issues on their
own; skip one unless a real attacker gain follows from it — memory
corruption, an auth or access-control bypass, secret disclosure, injection,
or similar (any bug class, not just memory-safety):

- **trusted-caller / caller-contract misuse** — a NULL-deref or crash
  reachable only because a trusted caller passed NULL or out-of-contract
  arguments to an API that documents valid ones;
- **OOM / allocation-failure only** — a NULL crash, leaked allocation, or
  stale error flag when a single allocation fails (not attacker-driven
  resource exhaustion, which is in scope);
- **debug-only `assert` / `*_CHECK`** that the shipped release build
  compiles out;
- **non-product surface** — code that does not ship in the product: test or
  fuzz drivers, examples, demos, build or codegen scripts.

Recall-safe: if you cannot tell whether input reaches it, whether the file
ships, or whether a real attacker gain follows, report it — a missed bug
costs more than a weak lead the validator can drop.
